<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>So I have been playing around with Fedora for quite a while and notice some difference in some implementation.</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>I have noticed before fedora can freely access my Arch root including home btrfs subvolume top level while Arch cannot access it directly. UNLESS, Fedora / drive is mounted by command.</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>mount /dev/sdx3 /mnt -o subvolid=5</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>So I have done same thing on my Arch with BTRFS subvolumes</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>Steps on how to do it:</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p># btrfs subvolume list /</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>find the ID number of @ or / subvolume. In my case was 260</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p># btrfs subvolume set-default 260 /</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>I have tested it and fedora or any other linux cannot freely access my Arch btrfs top-level subvolume unless mounted as above.</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>Hope this helps</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/Ja-KooLit"> /u/Ja-KooLit </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/w5x9w8/arch_btrfs_subvolumes_partial_restricting_access/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/w5x9w8/arch_btrfs_subvolumes_partial_restricting_access/">[comments]</a></span>